Apple=E2=80=99s E.U. Fine
-----------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/eus-top-court-uphol=
ds-14-35-billion-apple-tax-bill-in-irish-benefits-case-e589b435 ) :

Apple and Alphabet=E2=80=99s Google lost attempts to overturn multibillion-=
dollar rulings in the European Union on Tuesday, marking a win for competit=
ion authorities in the bloc in their efforts to rein in alleged abuses by b=
ig tech companies.

The European Court of Justice, the bloc=E2=80=99s highest court, upheld an =
order for Ireland to recoup up to 13 billion euros, equivalent to $14.35 bi=
llion, plus interest in taxes from Apple. The European Commission, the EU=
=E2=80=99s executive arm, said in 2016 that Ireland had granted Apple benef=
its in contravention of EU state-aid rules, allowing the tech giant to pay =
substantially less tax than it owed. The commission asked Ireland to retrie=
ve the sum in allegedly unpaid taxes between 2003 and 2014, plus interest, =
an order that both Apple and the Irish government appealed.

Years later, the General Court of the European Union, the bloc=E2=80=99s se=
cond-highest, annulled the commission=E2=80=99s decision because it said of=
ficials had failed to meet the legal standards in showing that Apple was gi=
ven special treatment. The ECJ has now axed that ruling, saying the lower c=
ourt was wrong in its reasoning. Apple can=E2=80=99t appeal.

I=E2=80=99m not surprised that the Apple and Google decisions are being lum=
ped together; they are multi-billion euro fines from European regulators cr=
acking down on big tech, right? In fact, the cases are quite different, and=
 even though the numbers are bigger for Apple, this case is, in the grand s=
cheme of things, less of a big deal.

I wrote extensively about this case when the European Commission first rule=
d on it in 2016 ( https://stratechery.com/2016/apples-eu-tax-problem-how-ap=
ple-pays-taxeseventually-everyone-is-a-loser/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUz=
I1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJh=
dWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWUR=
LYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE2L2FwcG=
xlcy1ldS10YXgtcHJvYmxlbS1ob3ctYXBwbGUtcGF5cy10YXhlc2V2ZW50dWFsbHktZXZlcnlvb=
mUtaXMtYS1sb3Nlci8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcyODY1MTk5MCwiaWF0IjoxNzI2MDU5OTkwLCJpc3Mi=
OiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCB=
hcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1Yi=
I6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.ZK1aj51DlTUC3kTjxg=
e3F-1GQvr1vYwTAS-i6ZfL4mH1-_UwwgBVB8KG6bJ3baglVhM4aCYdbwyHH7AXxkC_34oB5quIj=
70I932LMupTRnftVbTJelixj7PXOJ2FUS1RcFU-3krJFkfsQCc90MIQ3XTpDd-p5HZF9jjO6xSB=
sHaSrWMUEe51HnJW8B3InOuOMQ_eilxzFfxHBZR7ivQajTqJ2aV4FuwAPEuJAGBUb7ygtcXMndR=
rBFbbohWF2RiWHXhNB90N2gdQ236fTCwd5OcCgpDe5fGNxCseXgF6TVXNC4V70K01DSoCDSsTCA=
nq3-OVCzoJnho5Xkru3ACTqA ) ; that Update remains a decent overview of the i=
ssue, but to quickly summarize:

* Apple initially set up a factory in Cork, Ireland in 1980.
* In the early 1990s, Apple was looking for an entity through which to funn=
el its international revenue; it registered Apple Operations International =
(AOI) in Ireland, but managed and operated it from Cupertino. This, thanks =
to the differing tax regimes between Ireland (a territorial tax system) and=
 the United States (a global tax system that only collected taxes on profit=
s when they were repatriated) resulted in an entity that didn=E2=80=99t exi=
st anywhere; this was quite convenient for holding what eventually came to =
be hundreds of billions of dollars of profit without paying taxes.
* This scheme was based in Ireland thanks to a favorable ex ante ruling by =
the Irish tax authorities that they would only charge taxes on the original=
 Cork operation, given that the management and operations of AOI didn=E2=80=
=99t happen in Ireland.

This case was about that last bullet point. Specifically, the European Comm=
ission did not bring an antitrust case against Apple, but rather an unfair =
competition case against Ireland, accusing it of effectively subsidizing Ap=
ple via its tax interpretation. That is why this isn=E2=80=99t a fine: it=
=E2=80=99s a tax payment; Apple needs to pay taxes on AOI=E2=80=99s operati=
ons up to 2014 to Ireland.

Here=E2=80=99s the thing, though: Apple has already paid those taxes, back =
in 2018, when it repatriated $245 billion ( https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/17=
/it-looks-like-apple-is-bringing-back-home-nearly-all-of-its-250-billion-fo=
reign-cash.html ) in foreign profits, on which they paid a $38 billion tax =
bill to the U.S. Treasury; this was in response to provisions in the Trump =
tax bill mandating tax payments on foreign cash that had not been repatriat=
ed. To that end, this was what Apple said in its most recent 10-Q ( https:/=
/s2.q4cdn.com/470004039/files/doc_earnings/2024/q3/filing/_10-Q-Q3-2024-As-=
Filed.pdf ) :

On August 30, 2016, the European Commission (the =E2=80=9CCommission=E2=80=
=9D) announced its decision that Ireland granted state aid to the Company b=
y providing tax opinions in 1991 and 2007 concerning the tax allocation of =
profits of the Irish branches of two subsidiaries of the Company (the =E2=
=80=9CState Aid Decision=E2=80=9D). The State Aid Decision ordered Ireland =
to calculate and recover additional taxes from the Company for the period J=
une 2003 through December 2014. Irish legislative changes, effective as of =
January 2015, eliminated the application of the tax opinions from that date=
 forward. The Company and Ireland appealed the State Aid Decision to the Ge=
neral Court of the Court of Justice of the European Union (the =E2=80=9CGen=
eral Court=E2=80=9D). On July 15, 2020, the General Court annulled the Stat=
e Aid Decision. On September 25, 2020, the Commission appealed the General =
Court=E2=80=99s decision to the European Court of Justice (the =E2=80=9CECJ=
=E2=80=9D) and a hearing was held on May 23, 2023. A decision from the ECJ =
is expected in the fourth quarter of 2024. The Company believes it would be=
 eligible to claim a U.S. foreign tax credit for a portion of any increment=
al Irish corporate income taxes potentially due related to the State Aid De=
cision.

I am not a tax lawyer, but my assumption is that Apple will be able to clai=
m a foreign tax credit for the taxes it now has to pay Ireland, but will no=
t be able to claim a credit on the interest that has been charged (which am=
ounts to around =E2=82=AC7 billion). The company=E2=80=99s SEC filing ( htt=
ps://d18rn0p25nwr6d.cloudfront.net/CIK-0000320193/33ab9a1c-e116-4117-9323-2=
355cba0fa2f.pdf ) in response to this decision seems to confirm something a=
long those lines, as it warns of a one-time income charge of =E2=80=9Cup to=
 approximately $10 billion=E2=80=9D, which is =E2=80=9Cup to=E2=80=9D =E2=
=82=AC9 billion; presumably the missing =E2=82=AC9-11 billion is covered by=
 that tax credit. In other words, this decision is basically a transfer of =
money out of the U.S. Treasury to Ireland; one wonders if this will finally=
 motivate Washington to actually defend a U.S. tech company in Europe.

Apple=E2=80=99s Next Case?
------------------

What is worth highlighting is that 2015 change Apple noted in its 10-Q; at =
the end of 2015 Ireland caved into pressure and closed the =E2=80=9Ccompany=
 from nowhere=E2=80=9D loophole. Apple did three things in response:

* AOI became an Irish-resident entity which means it owed more taxes than b=
efore.
* AOI=E2=80=99s official operations moved to Jersey ( https://www.nytimes.c=
om/2017/11/06/world/apple-taxes-jersey.html ) , a small island in the Engli=
sh Channel that does not charge corporate taxes.
* AOI borrowed around =E2=82=AC300 billion which it spent acquiring intelle=
ctual property from Apple; this is a capital allowance that is depreciated =
over time, which just so happened to wipe out Apple=E2=80=99s tax liability=
.

All of this information is derived from this excellent blog post ( https://=
economic-incentives.blogspot.com/2018/01/what-apple-did-next.html ) ; the a=
uthor, Seamus Coffey ( https://x.com/seamuscoffey ) , has been tracking App=
le=E2=80=99s capital allowance ever since; the last of it was used up in 20=
22 ( https://economic-incentives.blogspot.com/2023/04/the-last-insight-into=
-apples-use-of.html ). It=E2=80=99s not clear if Apple will transfer more.

What is notable is this observation from the first post I linked, with rega=
rds to yesterday=E2=80=99s decision:

How might the European Commission view Apple=E2=80=99s decision to shift th=
e =E2=80=9Ccontract manufacturing=E2=80=9D activity to Ireland in 2015? If =
viewed through their lens could it be construed as tax avoidance? Absolutel=
y.

The logic of the state-aid decision is that, up to 2014, Apple owes tax on =
the profits from its =E2=80=9Ccontract manufacturing=E2=80=9D activity to I=
reland because the only substance the Commission could see that was able to=
 generate those profits was in Ireland. The Commission could not see eviden=
ce that the US-based board of directors was responsible for the profits so =
all the profits were attributed to the activities in Ireland. Of the =E2=82=
=AC13 billion figure suggested by the Commission around =E2=82=AC2.5 billio=
n will be due to profits earned in 2014.

As an aside, as I noted in my original Update linked above, while Apple=E2=
=80=99s tax avoidance strategies are those of a good fiduciary but terrible=
 citizen, this decision is pretty ridiculous; obviously Apple Inc. was cont=
rolling AOI. Regardless, continuing on with Coffey=E2=80=99s post:

In 2015, Apple carried out much the same functions in Ireland but now the s=
ales were executed and recorded in Ireland and the license for the IP was o=
nshored to Ireland. From the perspective of the Commission the tax liabilit=
y on the profits went from =E2=82=AC2.5 billion to nil. Is that reducing a =
tax liability?=E2=80=A6

If the Commission=E2=80=99s =E2=82=AC13 billion decision is upheld by the c=
ourts then Apple will owe =E2=82=AC2.5 billion of Corporation Tax for the =
=E2=82=AC20 billion of profit earned by ASI in 2014. In 2015, much the same=
 profit was earned by a related company in Ireland which carried out much t=
he same activity except it has paid a couple of hundred billion to buy the =
license for the IP underlying the activity.

Again, from an Irish perspective this isn=E2=80=99t a huge issue. The profi=
t linked to the IP wasn=E2=80=99t here in 2014 so wasn=E2=80=99t taxed here=
. The IP was onshored in 2015, which resulted in the profit being located h=
ere as the GDP changes illustrate. The profit was generated by an asset now=
 located here so the profit offset by the depreciation of that asset was in=
cluded in Ireland=E2=80=99s GNP. The company earning that profit had bought=
 a license giving it the right to use that IP and such a payment would typi=
cally be deductible for tax purposes. The appropriate Irish law was followe=
d appropriately.

But if you are the European Commission and your view is that =E2=82=AC2.5 b=
illion of tax is due to Ireland for 2014 then what else could you say but t=
hat the use of capital allowances in 2015 against the same profit (albeit i=
n a different company) had as one its main purposes the reduction in liabil=
ity to tax. Through the Commission=E2=80=99s lens such a claim for capital =
allowances would not be allowed per S291a(7)(c) though as well as showing t=
hat there was a reduction in the tax liability they would also have to show=
 that it was not a bona fide commercial transaction so it is far from clear=
 that such a view would hold up under legal scrutiny.

This means that what is at stake when the original state-aid decision is fi=
nally decided by the courts may not just be the =E2=82=AC13 billion plus in=
terest for the period from 2004 to 2014 but possibly also =E2=82=AC2.5 bill=
ion to =E2=82=AC3 billion for every year since. There would be no basis to =
challenge the use of capital allowances in the 2015 restructure if the =E2=
=82=AC13 billion ruling isn=E2=80=99t upheld.

Well, the =E2=82=AC13 billion ruling was just upheld, so there might be ano=
ther case on the way. And, once again, the entity actually paying the price=
 will be the U.S. Treasury.

As for the Google case, the court upheld the ruling, which was also upheld =
by the General Court (the Apple case was originally overturned, and now ove=
rturned again). Therefore, I don=E2=80=99t have anything to add beyond what=
 I wrote at the time in Ends, Means, and Antitrust ( https://stratechery.co=
m/2017/ends-means-and-antitrust/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI=
6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhd=
GVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwi=
